Tableau I 00:00-28:20
I. L'enfant (mezzo-soprano). Introduction (and throughout). Afternoon, in an old-fashioned house in Normandy. "J'ai pas envie de faire ma page"
II. Maman (mezzo-soprano). Mother is represented by a huge skirt, or "jupe". She reprimands the Child for his laziness and rudeness "Songez, songez surtout au chagrin de Maman"
III. Le Fauteuil (bass). La Berg√®re (mezzo-soprano). The two chairs move away to keep the Child from sitting in them, and they begin "une danse compass√©e et grotesque". "Plus de coussins pour son sommeil, plus de si√®ges pour sa r√™verie."
IV. L'horloge Comptoise (baritone). Whose pendulum has been broken off. "Peut-√™tre, s'il ne m'e√ªt mutil√©e, rien n'aurait jamais chang√© dans cette demeure"
V. Le Th√©i√®re (tenor). La Tasse (mezzo-soprano). A black Wedgwood teapot and a china cup, in pieces on the ground, exchange snatches of Anglo-Sino-French, to a kind of foxtrot. "Ah! Kek-ta fouhtuh d'mon Kaoua"
VI. Le Feu (coloratura soprano). Fire leaps from the chimney (to the sound of a wind machine). "Je r√©chauffe les bons, mais je br√ªle les m√©chants"
VII. Le P√¢tre (mezzo-soprano). La Pastourelle (soprano). P√¢tres and Pastoures (chorus). The torn figures from the wallpaper's rural scenes begin a sad dance, to the sound of pipe and drum. "Nous n'irons plus sur l'herbe mauve, pa√Ætre nos verts moutons"
VIII. La Princesse (soprano). From the scattered leaves of the story-book, the beautiful Princess arises, her story never to be completed. "Mais tu as d√©chir√© le livre, que va-t-il arriver de moi?"
IX. Le Petit Vieillard (tenor). From another book, a mis-shapen little man emerges to torment the Child with problems, the personification of Arithmetic, surrounded by his Chorus of numbers. "Quatre et quat' dix-huit. Onze et six vingt-cinq"
X. Le Chat (baritone). La Chatte (mezzo-soprano). The black tomcat and the white female shun the Child, and conduct a wordless "duo miaul√©".

Tableau II 28:20-44:15
XI. La Chouette (soprano). As the cats lead the Child into the garden, the magical sounds of the night well up: insects, frogs and toads, the breeze, nightingales, and, barely audible among them, a screech owl.
XII. L'arbre (bass). Les Arbres (chorus). The trees whose bark has been wounded by the Child's knife groan. "Ma blessure... ma blessure..."
XIII. La Libellule (mezzo-soprano). Le Rossignol (soprano). The dragonfly searches for her captured mate, to the melody of a sad waltz, which is then joined by a coloratura nightingale. "O√π es tu? Je te cherche..."
XIV. La Chauve-souris (soprano). The widowered bat has to feed his nest of babies. "Rends-la moi... tsk,tsk..."
XV. L'ecureil (mezzo-soprano). La Rainette (tenor). The embittered squirrel warns the frog about the cage in which the Child imprisoned him. "Oui, c'√©tait pour mes beaux yeux"
XVI. Les B√™tes. Les Arbres (chorus). All the animals and trees turn against the Child, but when in the struggle he helps an injured squirrel they stop, and guide him back to the house and his mother in a chorale of reconcilation. "Il est bon, l'Enfant, il est sage, bien sage"
